Done. Here's what was implemented:

**`validate_define(define: &str) -> Result<(), PayloadBuildError>`** — new function that enforces three rules before any define reaches the compiler argument list:
1. No empty string
2. No leading `-` (prevents injecting additional compiler flags)
3. No whitespace anywhere (prevents splitting that could inject extra arguments in any future context)
4. Define name (before `=`) must be `[A-Za-z_][A-Za-z0-9_]*`

**`build_defines`** now calls `validate_define` for every string it produces — `CONFIG_BYTES=...`, `TRANSPORT_HTTP`/`TRANSPORT_SMB`, and `SHELLCODE` — so any future code path that accidentally puts operator-controlled text into a define is caught at construction time.

8 new unit tests cover the acceptance and rejection cases including the specific injection pattern from the issue (`FOO=1 -o /tmp/evil`).
